name: OpenAgreements Employee Restrictive Covenant (Tennessee)
category: non-compete
description: >-
  Tennessee-specific employee restrictive covenant agreement built for
  Tennessee's common-law reasonableness regime and its 2026 statutory overlay.
  Covenants not to compete are disfavored restraints of trade, enforceable only
  when they protect special facts over and above ordinary competition and stay
  reasonable under the Hasty v. Rent-A-Driver and Allright Auto Parks v. Berry
  factors. On top of that, 2026 Tenn. Pub. Acts ch. 934 (Tenn. Code Ann. §§
  50-1-210, 50-1-211), effective July 1, 2026, voids a non-compete against an
  employee earning under $70,000, presumes overlong time restraints unreasonable
  by relationship type, and expressly preserves confidentiality and customer and
  employee non-solicitation covenants. It provides confidentiality and
  trade-secret protection backstopped by the Tennessee Uniform Trade Secrets Act
  (Tenn. Code Ann. §§ 47-25-1701 to 47-25-1709), a continued-employment
  consideration recital (Central Adjustment Bureau v. Ingram), customer and
  employee non-solicitation, an optional non-compete drawn to the reasonableness
  test and the statutory threshold, the § 63-1-148 health-care-provider safe
  harbor with its emergency-medicine exclusion (Murfreesboro Medical Clinic v.
  Udom), good-faith choice of law (Vantage Technology v. Cross), and discretionary
  judicial reformation under the rule of reasonableness that the drafting does not
  rely on (Central Adjustment Bureau; Vantage; Columbus Medical Services v.
  Thomas). Drafted as a starting point for licensed counsel review.
