  - name: noncompete_included
    type: boolean
    description: >-
      Whether the non-competition covenant is included. Tennessee treats a
      non-compete as a disfavored restraint of trade that is not void per se and
      is enforceable only when it protects special facts over and above ordinary
      competition and is reasonable under Tennessee's common-law factors. For
      agreements entered into, renewed, or amended on or after July 1, 2026, the
      covenant is also void if the employee's annualized compensation is under
      $70,000, and its duration is tested against the relationship-based time
      presumptions in Tennessee's 2026 non-compete statute.
    display_label: Non-Competition Included
    default: false
    section: Non-Competition
    rationale_source: editorial
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Conservative default. The non-compete is the most heavily scrutinized
      covenant, and a customer non-solicit expressly preserved by Tennessee's
      2026 non-compete statute often protects the employer as well. Include only
      after confirming special facts over and above ordinary competition exist,
      the employee's annualized compensation is at least $70,000 for a covenant
      governed by the 2026 statute, the duration is within the applicable
      statutory presumption window, and the Tennessee health-care-provider safe
      harbor and emergency-medicine exclusion are addressed.
  - name: noncompete_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of non-competition restriction
    display_label: Non-Competition Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: Non-Competition
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.tennessee.keep-time-restraints-within-the-statutory-presumption-windows
    default_value_rationale: >-
      For a covenant governed by the 2026 statute, a court presumes a restraint
      against a former employee or independent contractor reasonable in time when
      it is two years or less, measured from the date the relationship
      terminates, and presumes a longer term unreasonable. 12 months sits well
      within that window; counsel should size it to the actual role and market
      rather than default to the outer bound.
  - name: territory
